 Portuguese explorers competed to find their elusive source. But when the Portuguese finally reached the spice islands of the Moluccas in 1511, they set in motion a fierce competition for control. Roger Crowley shows how this struggle shaped the modern world. From 1511 to 1571, European powers linked up the oceans, established vast maritime empires, and gave birth to global trade, all in the attempt to control the supply of spices. Taking us on voyages from the dockyards of Seville to the vastness of the Pacific, the volcanic Spice Islands of Indonesia, the Arctic Circle, and the coasts of China, this is a narrative history rich in vivid eyewitness accounts of the adventures, shipwrecks, and sieges that formed the first colonial encounters—and remade the world economy for centuries to follow.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSpice tradexHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074979340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300277210?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300277210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300277210/original  a978-3-11-074979-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles